The paper is focused on the complexity of distributed graph problems in the LOCAL model, which is a well-studied model in distributed computing. Therefore, cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) are the most likely categories. The paper also discusses the randomized and deterministic complexity of classic distributed graph problems, which suggests that cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.IT (Information Theory) are also possible categories. Finally, the paper introduces a complexity-theoretic framework to shed light on the role of randomness in the LOCAL model, which could potentially fall under cs.LG (Machine Learning).
